\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Required Communication Channels
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The designated work order system (Redmine) is the authoritative channel for all service requests,
 technical communications,
 and service lifecycle documentation.
 Work order records are subject to retention obligations under the Nevada Local Government Records Retention Schedule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Channel Mandate
\series default
:
 Unless the work order system is inaccessible due to a documented system outage,
 all service requests and IT responses shall be initiated,
 tracked,
 and closed within the work order system.
 Channel exceptions require justification documented in the relevant work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Out-of-Band Summarization
\series default
:
 Verbal or informal communications —
 including hallway conversations,
 phone calls,
 and instant messages —
 shall be summarized and entered into the relevant work order by the IT staff member conducting or receiving the communication.
 This entry shall be completed within one (1) business day of the interaction,
 or prior to ticket closure,
 whichever occurs first.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Constraint on Private Notes
\series default
:
 Standard,
 user-visible notes shall be the default for all ticket documentation.
 Private Notes shall only be utilized for the following authorized purposes:
 documenting internal security vulnerabilities or unpatched exploit data;
 redacting or handling accidental spillage of PII,
 PHI,
 or CJI;
 documenting personnel-sensitive actions such as HR-directed account lockouts;
 and internal technical diagnostics that would not be meaningful for the end user.
 Private Notes remain subject to applicable retention obligations and public records law.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Vendor and External Partner Communications
\series default
:
 Communications with vendors or external partners shall likewise be summarized in the relevant work order or project record.
 Where such communications occur outside the work order system (e.g.,
 via vendor portal,
 email,
 or phone),
 IT staff shall document the substance of those communications in Redmine within one (1) business day.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Written Communication as Default
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Written communication is the departmental standard.
 It reduces ambiguity,
 supports auditability,
 and ensures continuity of service knowledge across staff.
 Requests from County personnel shall be directed to the work order system rather than resolved through informal verbal channels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 English Prime (E-Prime) Guidance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
IT personnel may apply English Prime (E-Prime) principles in written communications —
 specifically,
 avoiding forms of the verb "to be" when greater precision or flexibility would benefit the communication.
 This practice reduces false certainty in service communications and naturally invites end-user confirmation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
For example:
 "This appears to be resolved" or "This should be working now —
 please verify" invites the user to confirm,
 whereas "This is fixed" places the user in a position of either agreement or conflict.
 The goal is not to introduce ambiguity,
 but to invite collaborative confirmation and reduce premature closure of unresolved issues.
 E-Prime is guidance,
 not a rigid rule;
 personnel may apply it where it improves communication clarity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Disambiguation and Clarity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
IT personnel shall communicate in plain language accessible to non-technical County staff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Unexplained acronyms and technical jargon shall not be used in end-user communications without definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
When multiple questions are required,
 they shall be numbered individually.
 Example:
 "1.
 When did the issue begin?
 2.
 What error message appears?
 3.
 Can you reproduce the issue consistently?" This format reduces missed answers and vague responses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Compound or binary questions that allow for ambiguous single-word answers shall be avoided.
 Example:
 "Can I come before or after lunch?" invites the response "Yes." The clearer form is "Can I come before lunch?
 If not,
 what time after lunch works for you?" The goal is not to talk down to users,
 but to provide prompts precise enough that their responses are actionable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Vendor and External Partner Communications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
When communicating with vendors or external partners on behalf of the Department,
 IT personnel shall maintain the same documentation and clarity standards as for end-user communications.
 Commitments made to vendors —
 including agreed timelines,
 approved scopes,
 or escalation acknowledgments —
 shall be confirmed in writing and documented in the relevant work order or contract record.
 IT personnel shall not communicate acceptance of deliverables,
 changes to contracted scope,
 or authorization of additional costs without IT Director approval in accordance with 
\series bold
Policies 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and 
\series bold

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Accountability in Language
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
IT personnel shall use precise language of personal and departmental accountability in service communications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Use "I" when taking personal responsibility for a specific action or commitment.
 Example:
 "I will follow up with you by 3:00 PM today."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Use "We" when speaking on behalf of the Department as a whole.
 Example:
 "We received your request and are currently reviewing it."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Do not imply action,
 approval,
 or authority beyond the scope of your assigned role.
 Commitments that exceed role authority shall be escalated to the designated authority as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and the Service Catalog before being communicated to the user or vendor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Information Spillage Prevention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
ECIO personnel shall not instruct or permit end users to transmit passwords,
 Criminal Justice Information (CJI),
 or unprotected Personally Identifiable Information (PII) through standard work order notes or unencrypted email.
 If a user transmits such data into a work order,
 the receiving IT staff member shall immediately move the data to a Private Note,
 sanitize the user-facing record,
 and initiate the data spillage protocols required by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Identification and Reporting Procedures),
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 SI-12 (Information Management and Retention).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.8 Communication During Service Incidents
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
During active service incidents or outages,
 the communication standards defined in this policy remain in effect for documentation and channel requirements.
 Specific protocols governing the frequency,
 content,
 and escalation of communications during active incident response —
 including user notification timelines and external reporting obligations —
 are defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 IT personnel shall not communicate incident scope,
 affected systems,
 or estimated recovery timelines to external parties,
 media,
 or non-IT County staff without IT Director authorization.
\end_layout

